results.name: a(n) is the number of trinomials x^n + x^k + 1 that are irreducible over GF(2) for some k with n > k > 0.
comment: Brent, Hart, Kruppa, and Zimmermann found that a(57885161) = 0. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 30 2013
link: T. D. Noe, Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..500
Paul Zimmermann, There is no primitive trinomial of degree 57885161 over GF(2), posting to NMBRTHRY mailing list [alternate link]
example: a(7) = 4 because 1 + x + x^7 = 1 + x + x^7, 1 + x^2 + x^7 = (1 + x + x^2)*(1 + x + x^2 + x^4 + x^5), 1 + x^3 + x^7 = 1 + x^3 + x^7, 1 + x^4 + x^7 = 1 + x^4 + x^7, 1 + x^5 + x^7 = (1 + x + x^2)*(1 + x + x^3 + x^4 + x^5) and 1 + x^6 + x^7 = 1 + x^6 + x^7. Thus there are 4 trinomial expressions which cannot be factored over GF(2) and 2 trinomial expressions which do factor.
xref: For n such that a(n) > 0 see A073571.
Cf. A014580 (irreducible polynomials over GF(2) encoded as binary numbers), A344146.
